  </div>
</section>

<section id="seo-faq" class="section-sm" style="border-top:1px solid var(--hairline);">
  <div class="container" style="max-width:880px;">
    <h2 class="heading-lg" style="margin-bottom:20px; text-align:left;">Frequently Asked Questions — Compress PDF & Images</h2>
    <div class="body-md" style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:12px; color:var(--body);">
      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">Is Compressly free to use?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Yes — Compressly is completely free to use. There is no signup required, no watermarks, and no hidden fees.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">Are my images uploaded to a server?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">No. Compression runs locally in your browser using the Canvas API and other browser APIs. Your files are not uploaded to our servers.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">What quality setting should I use?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">For general web use, 60–80% quality usually offers the best balance between file size and visible quality. For photos, try 70–80%; for aggressive size reduction, try 40–60%.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">Can I compress multiple images at once?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Yes — select or drag multiple files into the tool and use the "Compress All" action to batch-process images.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">Does PNG compression work the same way?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">PNG files are handled differently; Compressly optimizes PNGs and allows converting PNG to JPG when appropriate for better compression.</div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress a PDF?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Use Compressly by dragging your PDF into the tool, selecting a compression quality, and clicking Compress. The tool re-encodes embedded images to reduce overall file size while preserving text and layout.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress PDF files?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Batch-upload one or more PDFs, pick a quality level, and compress. You can preview before downloading and repeat with a lower quality for smaller sizes.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress a file?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">If the file is an image or PDF, use Compressly to optimize it in-browser. For other file types, consider zipping or using specific optimizers for that format.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress a PDF file?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Open Compressly, upload the PDF, adjust the image quality slider, and compress. The result downloads immediately—no uploads to our servers.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress a PDF for free?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Compressly is free: compress PDFs and images entirely in your browser without creating an account. Choose lower quality to achieve smaller sizes.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress PDF file size?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Reduce embedded image quality, remove unnecessary images, or downsample high-resolution images. Compressly focuses on image recompression inside PDFs to reduce file size effectively.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress an image?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Upload JPG, PNG, or WEBP, choose a quality percentage, and compress. For photos, 60–80% often provides good balance between size and quality.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">How to compress a PDF on Mac?</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">On macOS, you can use Preview > Export to create a smaller file, or use Compressly in your browser for more control over image quality and batch processing.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">Compress PDF to 100KB / 200KB / 500KB / 1MB</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Target sizes depend on input content. To reach small targets like 100KB, reduce image quality and remove pages/images. Try multiple passes with lower quality settings; extremely small targets may sacrifice visible quality.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">iLovePDF compress PDF — comparison</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">iLovePDF is a popular online service that also compresses PDFs. Unlike some services, Compressly processes files locally in your browser for improved privacy—choose the tool that matches your privacy needs.</div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary style="font-weight:600; cursor:pointer;">Free compress PDF / Compress PDF to 1MB free</summary>
        <div style="margin-top:8px;">Compressly offers free, in-browser compression that can often reach targets like 1MB depending on the original file. Experiment with quality settings to balance size and readability.</div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

